description.text:
This is a simple, screwless, snap-on extension to the stock cooler for the Duplicator i3 Plus (Maker Select Plus) for better cooling and air distribution. Unlike most cooling attachments, this component extends the existing stock cooling block/frame, rather than completely replacing it. It is easy and quick to print, and easy to install.

This may or may not be compatible with the Duplicator i3 v2.x; I'm not sure because I don't own one. Please leave a comment with your experience.

2017/01/22 Update: Added mcooler_higher file that is a few millimeters higher from the build plate if the original hangs too low for your setup.

Rafts:

Yes

No

Resolution:

0.1mm

Doesn't Matter

Notes:

The default orientation of the STL file is not the ideal printing orientation. Rotate the model 90 degrees so the angled extension on the exhaust end forms a ~40 degree angle with the ground, as shown in the 4th photo. The overhang shouldn't be too difficult for your printer to handle (consider a slower print speed if you have problems).

Installation

Unscrew the two vertical screws that mount the cooling "block" (large black piece shaped like a triangle, in pictures) to the printer. Then, unscrew the two corner screws on the 40mm fan to remove it from the block.

Insert the model through the large circular fan hole, and push it through the exhaust slit, until the two small triangular nubs on the bottom of the model snap it in place (see photos). Finally, reattach the 40mm fan and the block to the printer.

If you have difficulty fitting the model through the exhaust slit, you may have to slightly sand down the sides of the model. This is due to manufacturing variations in the cooling block.

title: Gift Card Box / Holder and Photo Frame

description.text: We give a lot of gift cards during the holidays...I don't like it that much, but what do you do when buying for people who just don't need anything (nor really want anything). So I came up with this little gift card carrier that has a built in photo frame. Instead of just giving the gift card I can give it in a little box that has a little extra value. You could also put a little note in the frame instead of a picture...or whatever you would like

Printer:

PowerSpec 3D Pro

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.20

Infill:

30%

Notes:

I've designed this to be printed with no supports, which is why it's in 3 pieces. It's really an easy print and with my printer and at .20mm layer height...layer lines are pretty much impossible to see. It's also kinda cool that since all the large visible surfaces are printed facing down, they get a nice smooth texture.

I've been using Inland PLA I get from MicroCenter as well as some ProtoPasta carbon fiber infused PLA as well. With the 3 piece design you can get a multi color object while using a single head printer.

I do use a brim with any print that has a large contact patch with the build-plate. This really helps to keep the corners from lifting. You might not need this as it is printer dependent (and is a problem with heated build plates). If you can get buy without a brim, you'll have zero post printing clean-up.

I have included a blank inner frame/matte piece that will allow you to use a custom message in the upper opening. Just center the text in the object and place 66.35mm from the lower Y axis edge (It's an oddball location I know....you can round up or down and be ok, but that is exactly where I have the text located).

So the four pieces in this design are supposed to have a snug fit. For a looser fit, just sand the sides down a bit. I don't want mine to fall apart before or while it is given, so I leave them pretty snug.

The little stand is especially tight (it needs to be) and tough to get in place, but fits fine with a little persuasion. Just shove the base end in the hole first, press down on the mid part, then if the top doesn't snap in...give it a whack with the end of a pen or something similar (I use the blunt end of a excacto knife) and it will pop into place.

So, That Just Happened

By many accounts and for so many reasons, 2016 has been one dumpster fire of a year.

So, we at PDX Hackerspace thought, why not commemorate it with your very own 2016 Dumpster Fire Ornament?

What You'll Need

AAA battery holder with on/off switch (or a CR2032 in a pinch)
https://www.amazon.com/uxcell-Battery-Holder-Wired-Switch/dp/B00H8WINGG

Dumpster Fire LEDs
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B017TR7EOQ/

Wire for Dumpster Lid and Ornament Hanger
https://www.amazon.com/Decora-Gauge-Green-Floral-Package/dp/B010P9NW8M/

3D Print Instructions

Some resizing is needed for the flame, depending on if you want to tape together a CR2032/LED or solder and tape the AAA pack. We printed our flames using TPE filament with 0% fill and 1 or 2 perimeter layers, no supports, no raft.

For the AAA pack, the Flame should be resized to ~50mm width x ~35mm height x ~35mm depth.

For the CR2032 battery, resize the Flame to ~50mm width x ~50mm height x ~35mm depth.

If anyone needs more detailed instructions for assembly, let us know!

Yes, it's yet another 3D printable Yoda! Today, I offer you the classicYoda model, hollowed out and turned into a cute coin bank. Years ago, Yoda was one of my very first 3D prints. At the time, I didn't know how to cut a hole for a coin slot (I just printed it hollow, cut a hole and then took a file to it, LOL!) or create a screw-on cover for the bottom of the bank. So this version is just my way of revisiting an earlier attempt, with an improved, yet still easy to print, design.

Print this you must!

Here's how I made it:
1) First, I measured some coins. I wanted the coin slot and the hole in the bottom to be able to fit a coin the size of a US or Canadian quarter, which is about 23mm in diameter. I found a suitable Yoda model and loaded it into Meshmixer. Then, Edit > Make Hollow, 1mm walls. Export as STL.
2) Load STL into Microsoft 3D Builder, Insert > Add cube, resize to 23mm length and 2mm width, position to desired location of slot, Edit > Subtract.
3) I used the screw section of my recently uploaded Smart Spool, cut (Edit > Split) to a smaller height, then made a copy and used that to Subtract a hole in that shape from the bottom of the model. I decreased the size of the screw-on cover 2% to improve the fit and saved the file as STL.
4) I reloaded the model into 3D Builder and it reported that the model needed repairs. I let it complete the repairs, resized it to 85mm height (yielding a coin slot roughly 28mm long, about the size of a Canadian Toonie or a US Dollar coin) and then resaved a final version.
5) At this point, I decided to prepare two versions of the Yoda Coin Bank: one with the 28mm "XL" size coin slot, and a larger model (100mm high) with a smaller 23mm slot and bottom hole, suitable for smaller coins or printing at larger sizes. Both versions were prepared as described above and are available for download here.

Notes

  • Does not need infill to be specified. Model is pre-hollowed.
  • If you intend to resize this model smaller or you want to use coins larger than a quarter, use the XL hole version.
  • Thanks to Creative Tools for the original screw-threads design.
  • Print in green (or paint as shown here: http://www.thingiverse.com/make:76090) for maximum Yoda-ness.

Be creative! Think of some other possibilities:

  • Stick an LED light in the bottom.
  • Place this over an LED light on your Christmas tree.
  • Insert a roll of paper containing wise Yoda quotes and thread the paper through the slot in the top. Then, anytime you need guidance, just ask Yoda!

description.text:
I liked the simple yet effective design of TheKre8Groups' Another Filament Spool Holder.

http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:32204

My only issue with it was when using a spool of Makerbot ABS. the spool would wobble on the thin spindle. I wanted the spool to roll easily, with as little wobble as possible.

This remix of the spindle cuts it apart, and adds an insert so the two parts can be joined. I also added two guide rings to keep the spool centered. The spool insert is sized for most Makerbot ABS filament spools. I added an end plate to stop the spool from working itself off the insert, but my experience so far is that the end plate is probably not needed. If you remix this for spools from other manufacturers, the end plate may come in handy.

The result is a spool that rolls easier and with more stability. It also raises the height of the spool, creating additional clearance underneath.

This should be adaptable to any manufacturer's spool by adjusting the dimensions of the insert.

description.text: Rostock is a delta robot 3D printer. This part is the top bracket that holds a pair of 8mm smooth rods, two ball bearings, a micro switch (endstop) and a plywood board. Newer versions of the OpenSCAD source files will be published here: https://github.com/jcrocholl/rostock

Print three of these and install them at 120 degree angles on a plywood board (see RostockBaseDims.pdf by Modpod http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:24973 or print the drill jig http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:25000). The plywood mounting holes are sized to work with #11 wood screws or M4 screws, no nuts needed. Clamp the smooth rod with 16mm M3 screws, washer on the outside, hex nut on the inside. Stainless steel fasteners are recommended. 30mm M8 socket screw holds two 608 bearings (skateboard bearings) followed by two M8 washers, then the printed part, another M8 washer, and a M8 hex nut. The printed part forces a 2 degree upward tilt for the M8 screw, which will prevent the timing belt from falling off. I like to add a printed plastic flange ring on the outside of the rear bearing. UPDATE: It's better if you can use a flanged 608 bearing, http://www.vxb.com/page/bearings/PROD/F608ZZ works really well, see pictures. The micro switch is the common ZM series with 9.5mm center distance between the mounting screws. If you use M2.5x12 or similar, they will screw directly into the plastic, no nuts needed.

title: 7/8 Cup (Dog Food) Scoop
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I have two yellow labs, each is fed 2 cups of food a day: 1 cup in the morning, and 1 cup at 5:00 PM.
After a few months of using a new scoop, I noticed they gained a bit of weight. The scoop happens to hold a bit more than 1 cup.
I decided to make a new scoop that holds 7/8 cup when level, and about 1 cup when heaping, the normal way we scoop the food into the cup.
This was designed with a fairly calibrated Cupcake CNC with a MK5 extruder in mind.

• Download the .stl file. Scale if necessary.
  • Slice-n-dice it.
  • Print, with the 3D Printer. PLA would be the strongest material.
  • Remove the extra support structures so that it looks like the one in the picture.
  • Check that it holds enough food.
  • Put in dog food container.
  • ....
  • Profit.
    • Source files are attached if you need to adjust the amount of food to hold. I used this equation on Wolfram|Alpha: " cube root of (convert 7/8 cup to cubic millimeters) " to produce the amount of millimeters needed on the inside edges of the cube holding the food.

description.text: A friction-fit easy-grab medicine bottle topper for cat (and possibly other animals and/or human) medicine bottles. I have some cat medicine that comes in a bottle with a snap-on cap. The top is perfectly designed to fit a syringe (the squirt down the throat type, not the sharp pointy type), but it is absolutely not designed to frequently open and close. There is no easy way to grip it except by the retaining plastic strap that prevents you from losing the lid and after a few days, that snaps off. After that you need fingernails or pliers. I designed this oversized cap to tightly fit over the existing cap. It gives you just the right sort of leverage to pull off the cap. As a side-effect of the design, the top also provides a large surface on which to write a quick dosage reference. (But please don't mix up the caps if you have multiple bottles!) The specific bottle this is sized for has a cap that is 14mm across and is 7mm high. Feel free to use the OpenSCAD source file to alter, if needed. The constants up top are very friendly to modification.
Just print and push over the cap. I used two extra shells and a 25% infill to make it a bit more solid than most prints. I did not have to use any sort of glue, though your mileage may vary.

description.text:
This is a housing for an optical filament run-out sensor. The center section allows for some adjustment for a sensor that comes poorly soldered thus in the wrong position like I ran into.You will need an M2 10mm bolt and nut to tighten the center adjustable piece and 2 small screws for the bottom cover. It is meant to mount in the Robo top slot. For info to incorporate this into a Robo 3D R1 see:

http://community.robo3d.com/index.php?threads/filament-runout-sensor-frs-upgrade-to-robo-r1-r1.17128/

12/27/2016 Added version 2 (all files with V2 in name). Version 2 incorporates the through slot (remixed) that comes with the Robo R1 and the filament out sensor swivels on the top of that through slot. It uses PTFE meant for 1.75 mm filament for the guide holes. The top piece is optional but the bottom piece is pretty much required. The bottom piece of PTFE inserts from the inside of the adjuster piece and is only about 4.5mm long. Without it you will probably get false triggers since there wouldn't be much to center the filament in the optical sensor. The top piece of PTFE is about 35mm long but is optional, This version requires an M2 12mm machine screw and an M2 insert (there wasn't room for a nut) The insert is melted into the bottom of the adjuster so that it is adjustable via the machine screw from the top. I printed the lightGuide with t-Glase which makes a fairly good light guide.

Note: I have modified the top housing to allow for more room incase the sensor is off center or whatever. It was a little tight before.

comments.text: A great update to this would be a filament oiler after the sensor for an all-in-one addon
comments.author: Scifideity

comments.text: I'm actually still trying to get my filament path working a little better. It's really easy for this to bind if there is any sideways tension on the filament. I use the stock ROBO filament holder so I'm pulling it from there and then through the sensor and into the stock guide in the top slot. Mounting the sensor in the top slot I was getting a lot of sideways pressure and some binding so I'm working on a guide for an improved path. I will post when I complete it. There will be a new outer shell also. I'm a little surprised the path is so critical to stop binding....The inner adjustment part is working great though. I thought about mounting directly above the extruder but wanted more filament left when it triggers.

description.text: There are some cat toys at the house that are particularly popular with the local residents. They are simple hollow spheres with cut-out slots. They are great for kitties to kick around â€” small and light. After staring at one for a few minutes, piecing out the geometry, I realized that this would make a great instructional design for an introduction to 3D CAD modeling using simple geometric shapes and boolean transforms. In the main image are the original (left), render (middle), and printed (right) versions of this object. The step-by-step process of building the model is on my blog, here: http://netninja.com/2012/03/24/from-atoms-to-bits-to-atoms-a-cat-toys-journey/ The final fully parametric OpenSCAD file is attached.

I used 2 shells in my Print-O-Matic settings.  If you print this on a MakerBot (or similar), you may want to enable printing supports and a raft in ReplicatorG.
REVISION HISTORY
v2 - Rotated, as per the great suggestion left in comments by MikeO.  This gives the design more resilience against the drooping found in the original version, meaning you probably won't need supports.
original - The original.  Even with supports enabled, the upper slats would overhang and the first few layers would droop a bit.  A small file or hobby blade will help clean that up.

Why did Tom Swift build his Outpost in Space? Tom Swift had several motives behind building his gigantic space station. When the book begins, Tom Swift needs a factory to manufacture his solar batteries. Since his solar batteries are energized most efficiently in outer space, Tom decided to build

"A space factory where we can manufacture solar batteries."

Phyl gasped. "A space factory!"

"Only a small one," Tom went on. "I'll locate it in an orbit fairly close to the earth, in order to make the job of building it as simple as possible. Say, a little over a thousand miles up. From down here, you could see it racing around the earth like a tiny moon."

However, Tom later greatly expanded his Outpost in Space after the following conversation with a group of engineers:

"Tom," said his father, "Mr. William Bruce is from the Consolidated Broadcasting Network, and is chairman of this committee of engineers from the major broadcasting companies. They've come to discuss a very important problem with us."

The group took seats, then Mr. Bruce addressed the Swifts. "I'll state our problem at once. As you know, high-frequency-signal coverage in its present form is far from being efficient. Distances are short, requiring many relay stations. Sometimes there's distortion. Also, sunspots or magnetic storms may wreck the broadcast completely."

"In fact," he went on, "any reliable system of short-wave broadcasting over great distances is practically hopeless with our present methods. However, there's one solution to this problem--"as a scientist, you've no doubt guessed what Iím about to propose."

"A space station?" Tom burst out in his enthusiasm.

Bruce nodded. "Exactly. Our committee has come to the conclusion that it's the only way we can hope to lick our broadcasting troubles--that is, by setting up a platform in space to which we can beam radio signals and have them relayed directly back to earth. Naturally, this would be a huge project. But we feel that Swift Enterprises is well fitted to undertake the job."

description.text:
This basic creature token is designed to hold up to three of my Magic: The Gathering Counters.

In case you're unfamiliar with my MtG counters, they are stackable counters that represent life, mana, keywords, loyalty, experience, energy, and other MtG symbols. Learn more and download them here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1815081

This basic token allows you to assemble your counters into creatures. Want to make a +2/+2 creature with flying and haste? No problem. Want to make a +2/+1 green-mana creature? You can do it with this.

The pointed edge indicates the front. To tap, simply turn 90 degrees.

If you want to specify mana color and save a slot, you can just print the token in the color of the mana. (For example, for black mana, print a black creature token.)

This is just a basic creature token, but the possibilities are endless. There could be tokens shaped as angels, dragons, servos, you name it. I would LOVE it if people would remix this basic holder into specific creatures. If you do, tag it with MtGCounters and make it a remix of this.
